04644nam a22007215i 9780691187327DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20182007nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97806911873277 a10.1515/97806911873272doi  a(DE-B1597)501830  a(OCoLC)1076408723  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aDS113.6b.L93 2007eb 7aSOC0480002bisacsh04a956.95/32231 aLybarger, Loren D., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aIdentity and Religion in Palestine :bThe Struggle between Islamism and Secularism in the Occupied Territories /cLoren D. Lybarger. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2018] 4cÂ©2007  a1 online resource (296 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPrinceton Studies in Muslim Politics ;v7900tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tForeword -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tNote on Transliterations -- tChronology of Events -- tCHAPTER ONE. Islamism and Secular Nationalism -- tCHAPTER TWO. The Secular-Nationalist Milieu -- tCHAPTER THREE. The Islamist Milieu -- tCHAPTER FOUR. Thawra Camp: A Case Study of Shifting Identities -- tCHAPTER FIVE. Karama Camp: Islamist-Secularist Dynamics in the Gaza Strip -- tEpilogue -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis remarkable book examines how the Islamist movement and its competition with secular-nationalist factions have transformed the identities of ordinary Palestinians since the first Palestinian uprising, or intifada, of the late 1980s. Drawing upon his years living in the region and more than eighty in-depth interviews, Loren Lybarger offers a riveting account of how activists within a society divided by religion, politics, class, age, and region have forged new identities in response to shifting conditions of occupation, peace negotiations, and the fragmentation of Palestinian life. Lybarger personally witnessed the tragic days of the first intifada, the subsequent Oslo Peace Process and its failures, and the new escalation of violence with the second intifada in 2000. He rejects the simplistic notion that Palestinians inevitably fall into one of two camps: pragmatists who are willing to accept territorial compromise, and extremists who reject compromise in favor of armed struggle. Listening carefully to Palestinians themselves, he reveals that the conflicts evident among the Islamists and secular nationalists are mirrored by the internal struggles and divided loyalties of individual Palestinians. Identity and Religion in Palestine is the first book of its kind in English to capture so faithfully the rich diversity of voices from this troubled part of the world. Lybarger provides vital insights into the complex social dynamics through which Islamism has reshaped what it means to be Palestinian.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aArab nationalismzPalestine. 0aIslam and politicszPalestine. 0aIslamzPalestine. 0aNational characteristics, Palestinian. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Islamic Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044250240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691187327zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780691187327423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780691187327.jpg  a978-3-11-044250-2  Princeton University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK